Ubuntu 22.04.4 LTS
Verilator 5.029 devel rev v5.028-49-g1c38744fd
```

Associative array methods do not currently report incompatible types. Though the LRM does not make it very clear what is incompatible. It simply states that the input should be "an index of the appropriate type for the array in question."

I would expect that an implicit cast is allowed only if
* if the input data type is integral, either 2-state or 4-state
* and its width is at least the width of the array key type

Otherwise there should be an error reported.

## Example

```systemverilog
module t;

    typedef bit [31:0] data_t;
    data_t dict [data_t];

    // verilator lint_off WIDTHTRUNC
    // verilator lint_off WIDTHEXPAND
    initial begin
        bit [31:0] a; // compatible but not explicitly data_t
        logic [63:0] b; // compatible but 4-state and longer than needed
        bit [7:0] c; // incompatible because too short

        dict.first(a); // correctly does not produce error, but doesn't compile
        dict.next(a); // correctly does not produce error, but doesn't compile

        dict.first(b); // correctly does not produce error, but doesn't compile
        dict.next(b); // correctly does not produce error, but doesn't compile

        dict.first(c); // incorrectly does not produce error
        dict.next(c); // incorrectly does not produce error

        $finish;
    end

endmodule
```
